Introduction

We have covered several topics related to data visualization and analysis from the principle of data visualization to producing good visuals. Now it is time to put it into practice. In this topic, we will present a case study and show the steps taken to analyse the given data.

As usual, we will first load the important packages.

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

Stroke Risk Factors

In this case study, we would like to use a data from kaggle on the topic of stroke and the factors associating to it. The data is originally from the Electronic Health Record (EHR) controlled by McKinsey & Company, and were used in a hackathon. Unfortunately, the original data with 43400 patients is no longer available. The current data shared in kaggle is only a subset of the original data.

Data Gathering and Objectives

In any data analysis, the source of data should be questioned first. Is it reliable? Can it be trusted? The importance of good and high quality data source must not be underestimated. If the data is unreliable, all the subsequent analysis becomes questionable. However, in our case study here, since the source is confidential, we would not be able to verify it and will only use it for educational purposes.

You can download the data from kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/fedesoriano/stroke-prediction-dataset) and read through the details.

After obtaining the data, we can then begin to ask, what is it that we want to achieve from our visualization? What is the objectives of this activity? The answer depends on the context, and what the reader/viewer expect to see from the data visualization. In our case study here, what we want to investigate is the various factors that may affect the chance of getting stroke.

In the data exploration part, we may want to ask these question:

  • How many patients are included in the data? How many of them have stroke, and how many of them do not have stroke?

  • What are the available columns in the data set?

  • What are the available possible risk factors in the data set?

Then, we would like to ask some more specific questions such as:

  • Which possible risk factors lead to higher chance of getting stroke?

  • How does the age distribution differs between those who have stroke and those that do not have stroke?

  • Similarly, how do the glucose level and BMI distribution differ between those who have stroke and those that do not have stroke?

To see all the available values in a column, we can use the unique() function.

unique(stroke_data$smoking_status)
## [1] "formerly smoked" "never smoked"    "smokes"          "Unknown"

Next, we may want to manipulate and clean the data. First, we want to change the 0’s to “No” and 1’s to “Yes” for readability. We also want to change the smoking status values to yes/no by only taking the patients that smokes as yes, and never or previously smoked or unknown as no. Additionally, we want to change the BMI column to numbers using as.numeric() function. Lastly, we want to limit our analysis to those age 10 years old and older.

stroke_data2 <- stroke_data %>%
  mutate(hypertension = ifelse(hypertension == 0, "No", "Yes"),
         heart_disease = ifelse(heart_disease == 0, "No", "Yes"),
         stroke = ifelse(stroke == 0, "No", "Yes"),
         smoke = ifelse(smoking_status %in% c("formerly smoked","smokes"),"Yes","No"),
         bmi = as.numeric(bmi)) %>%
  select(-"smoking_status") %>%
  filter(age >= 10)

str(stroke_data2)

Note that the visuals produced in this section are not finalized. Thus, we do not care much about the colors or themes and can make changes at the end. We are still exploring the data, but visually unlike before, and try to decide what story we can tell to the audience.

Association between variables

Next, let’s look at the association between the variables to see if there is any pattern or trend worth discussing. First, let’s look at the quantitative variables.

library(GGally)

ggpairs(stroke_data2,
        columns=c("age", "bmi", "avg_glucose_level"),
        lower = list(continuous = wrap("points", alpha=0.15, size=1)),
        diag = list(continuous = wrap("densityDiag", alpha=0.5)))

The correlation coefficient are all positives and statistically significant. There might be some pattern for the age versus bmi scatterplot but they are not worth discussing. Similarly for age versus average glucose level. As for the BMI versus average glucose level, we can see the data are concentrated at two points. One with lower BMI and average glucose level, and another at a higher BMI and average glucose level.

We can focus our attention to the two variables by just producing scatterplot using them and as well as stroke indicator. Note that in the code below, the arrange() function is used so that points for patients without stroke are placed first in the canvas, followed by patients with stroke. This is due to the overwhelming number of patients without stroke that makes it difficult if the points are overlapping.

ggplot(arrange(stroke_data2, stroke),
       aes(x=bmi, y=avg_glucose_level, color=stroke)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5)

From the scatterplot, we see that the BMI versus average glucose level are concentrated at two regions. However, patients without stroke are more concentrated in the bottom left region, whereas patients with stroke are not as concentrated as patients without stroke.

In the previous analysis for categorical data, we mentioned that ever married might be an important factor for stroke as those that have married tend to have higher percentage of stroke occurrences. However, does that make sense? Does getting married cause stroke? While it is true that those who have married have a higher tendency of getting stroke, the reason for it is possibly due to age, as those who are younger tend to be not married compared to older people.

df <- mutate(stroke_data2,
             ever_married = ifelse(ever_married == "Yes", "Has married",
                                   "Has not married"))

ggplot(arrange(df, stroke), aes(x=age, y=bmi, color=stroke)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5, position = position_jitter()) +
  facet_wrap(~ever_married, ncol = 1, labeller = )

In the chart above, we can see that yes, there are more people having stroke and married compared to those who have not married. But we can also see age-wise, those who have married tend to be older.

Findings and Finalizing Visuals

Now that we have explored the data and produced some visuals, we can proceed to finalizing the visuals to be shared to the audience. Our visuals must satisfy the objectives of the investigation. In our case study here, we want to identify which factors are associated with stroke, based on the data set.

Here are some findings we have found from the analysis:

  • Age is one of the main factor of stroke. Stroke tends to occur to those in the older age-range compared to the younger patients.

  • BMI may not be a factor of stroke, at least according to the data set. The distribution of BMI between the two groups are similar.

  • Average glucose level is possibly another factor of stroke with higher average glucose level associated with stroke occurrence.

  • Ever married is another factor associated with stroke. But this factor should be ignored as the association is due to its connection to age.

  • Hypertension, heart disease, and has smoked are other factors that are associated with stroke.

  • Work and residential types may not be associated with stroke.

From the findings, we can now proceed to finalizing visuals that share the same conclusions. At this stage, we need to think about what to include and what not to include when producing the visuals. For example, we may want to focus only on factors that are associated with stroke, and ignore BMI, ever married, and work and residential type variables from further analysis.

For the age and average glucose level, we can use the kernel density plot.

library(ggtext)

library(patchwork)

p1 / p2 / p3 &
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill="white")) &
  plot_annotation(title = "Distribution of patients <span style='color: #3CC3A8;'>without stroke</span> and <span style='color: #C33C57;'>with stroke</span>",

  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::label_percent())

Further Analysis

While visualization serves as a great tool for analysis, sometimes, we require something more concrete and objective. For this further analysis, we will be using logistic regression to identify the important factors. The logistic regression is a classification tool used to predict binary outcomes (yes/no, 0/1, etc.) using the explanatory variables.

The logistic regression uses the following model:

\[ \text{Probability}(y=1)=\frac{\exp(\beta_0+\beta_1 x_1 + \cdots + \beta_p x_p)}{1 + \exp(\beta_0+\beta_1 x_1 + \cdots + \beta_p x_p)} \]

where \(\beta_0\) is the intercept parameter, and \(\beta_1,...\beta_p\) are parameters associated with variables \(x_1,x_2,...,x_p\). Positive parameter values indicate that the variable has a positive effect of making \(y=1\).

In R, we can use logistic regression using the glm() function with the family = binomial argument.

df <- mutate(stroke_data2, stroke = ifelse(stroke=="Yes",1,0))
log_model <- glm(stroke ~ . -id, data=df, family=binomial)
summary(log_model)

The output shows the estimated parameters, standard error, z-value, and the p-value for each variable. Note that the p-value is for testing that the parameter is zero, or non-zero. A low p-value indicates that the data suggest that the parameter is non-zero, thus making the variable statistically significant.

Notice that only age, hypertension, heart disease, and average glucose level has p-value less than 0.1. These are the significant variables, according to the model. The parameter values are also positives, thus indicate that having higher age and average glucose level, or having hypertension or heart disease, lead to having higher probability of having stroke.

Conclusion

This topic gives an example of analyzing data using visualization. When presented with a data, there are several steps required to perform a full analysis. First, construct the objectives of the analysis and investigation. Then, explore the data to have a clear understanding of it. Next, explore the data visually and identify key findings that worth mentioning and discussed. And then lastly, list down all the findings together with the supporting visuals. We hope that the example shown in this topic helps you with analyzing data using visualization.
